content.theory:
## ACID Properties

Every database transaction guarantees four properties:

### Atomicity — All or Nothing

```sql
BEGIN TRANSACTION;
  UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 500 WHERE id = 1;
  UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 500 WHERE id = 2;
COMMIT;
-- If ANYTHING fails: both changes are rolled back
-- Money never vanishes or duplicates
```

The database writes changes to a **write-ahead log (WAL)** first. On crash recovery, it replays committed transactions and rolls back uncommitted ones.

### Consistency — Rules Are Never Broken

```sql
-- Constraint: balance must never go negative
ALTER TABLE accounts ADD CHECK (balance >= 0);

BEGIN;
  UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 500 WHERE id = 1;
  -- If this would make balance negative: constraint violation → auto-rollback
COMMIT;
```

### Isolation — Concurrent Transactions Don't Interfere

| Level | Dirty Reads | Non-Repeatable Reads | Phantom Rows |
|-------|------------|---------------------|-------------|
| READ UNCOMMITTED | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| READ COMMITTED | No | Yes | Yes |
| REPEATABLE READ | No | No | Yes |
| SERIALIZABLE | No | No | No |

Most databases default to **READ COMMITTED** — you see only committed data from other transactions.

### Durability — Committed Data Survives Crashes

Once COMMIT returns success, the data is on disk. Even if the server loses power 1ms later, the transaction is preserved.

## Practical Transaction Patterns

```sql
-- Pattern 1: Try/catch with rollback
BEGIN;
  -- Multiple operations...
  INSERT INTO audit_log (action, user_id) VALUES ('transfer', 1);
  UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 500 WHERE id = 1;
  UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 500 WHERE id = 2;
COMMIT;
-- On any error: ROLLBACK;

-- Pattern 2: Optimistic locking
SELECT balance, version FROM accounts WHERE id = 1;
-- Application processes...
UPDATE accounts 
  SET balance = new_balance, version = version + 1
  WHERE id = 1 AND version = old_version;
-- If 0 rows updated: someone else changed it → retry
```

expandableSections.content:
SERIALIZABLE is the strictest isolation level — transactions behave as if they ran one at a time. It prevents all anomalies but reduces concurrency.

Use it for:
- Financial calculations (account balances must be exact)
- Inventory management (can't oversell)
- Booking systems (can't double-book)

```sql
SET TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL SERIALIZABLE;
BEGIN;
  SELECT available_seats FROM flights WHERE id = 42;
  -- If >= 1:
  UPDATE flights SET available_seats = available_seats - 1 WHERE id = 42;
  INSERT INTO bookings (flight_id, passenger_id) VALUES (42, 100);
COMMIT;
```

With two concurrent bookings for the last seat, SERIALIZABLE ensures only one succeeds.
